Of note is that the database, after running the above has an empty **-wal** file :-

[![enter image description here][1]][1]

- Therefore the database has been fully check-pointed.

Copying this file from device explorer and opening in an SQLite tool (Navicat) shows :-

[![enter image description here][2]][2]

- i.e. the data inserted exists, as does the room_master_table and the android_metadata table

#Alternative to Close

An alternative to closing the database would be to use the [PRAGMA wal_checkpoint(?)](https://www.sqlite.org/pragma.html#pragma_wal_checkpoint)

If the DB class included the following methods :-

    public void checkpoint() {
        int attempts = 0;
        int max_attempts = 10;
        Cursor csr;
        SupportSQLiteDatabase ssd  = instance.getOpenHelper().getWritableDatabase();
        if (isWALOn(ssd)) {
            Log.d(&quot;CHKPOINTINFO&quot;,&quot;Attempt &quot; +  (attempts + 1));
            while (checkpoint(ssd) &gt; 0 &amp;&amp; attempts++ &lt; max_attempts) { }
        }
    }

    private boolean isWALOn(SupportSQLiteDatabase db) {
        boolean rv = false;
        Cursor csr = db.query(&quot;PRAGMA journal_mode&quot;);
        if  (csr.moveToFirst()) {
            if (csr.getString(0).toLowerCase().equals(&quot;wal&quot;)) rv = true;
        }
        csr.close();
        return rv;
    }

    private int checkpoint(SupportSQLiteDatabase db) {
        Log.d(&quot;CHKPOINTINFO&quot;,&quot;Attempting Database Ceckpoint&quot;);
        int blocked = 0;
        int pages_to_checkpoint = 0;
        int checkpointed_pages = 0;
        Cursor csr = db.query(&quot;PRAGMA wal_checkpoint(TRUNCATE)&quot;);
        if (csr.moveToFirst()) {
            blocked = csr.getInt(0);
            pages_to_checkpoint = csr.getInt(1);
            checkpointed_pages = csr.getInt(2);
        }
        csr.close();
        Log.d(&quot;CHKPOINTINFO&quot;,
                &quot;Checkpoint values Blocked = &quot; + blocked +
                        &quot; Pages to Checkpoint = &quot; + pages_to_checkpoint +
                        &quot; Pages Checkpointed = &quot; + checkpointed_pages
        );
        if (blocked &gt; 0) return -1;
        if (checkpointed_pages &lt; pages_to_checkpoint) return 1;
        return 0;
    }

- note Logging added for testing, typically this would be removed.

The instead of using `mDB.backup()`, `mDB.checkpoint()` could be used. The advantage of this is that the database remains open.

